plot out the distribution of things we want to kind of grok better with visuals.

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:13.920
As you can see here, we can start building our understanding of what our schema might

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:21.679
look like, right? So item is categorical, represented as strings. It has three possible

00:08:21.679 --> 00:08:29.119
values, apple, orange, banana. Price is a float, which is greater or equal to zero.

00:08:29.119 --> 00:08:35.919
And neither columns can contain null values.

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:43.520
So Pandera gives you a very simple way to translate this understanding into a schema.

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:50.200
So let's look at our first Pandera schema. First, we import the package. Then we create

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:56.159
a class. And hopefully, this is kind of clear enough, even if you're not super familiar

00:08:56.159 --> 00:09:00.080
with Python and classes. But hopefully, you can kind of read this and see what's going

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:08.719
on, where I'm subclassing DataFrameModel, and that's how I kind of define my schema.

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:16.679
Then I define some attributes in this class. So the item attribute is a string. And in

00:09:16.679 --> 00:09:21.119
this field function, I'm basically adding some more constraints that are not just the

00:09:21.119 --> 00:09:30.159
data type. So I'm saying item must be in this finite set of values. And similarly, price

00:09:30.159 --> 00:09:37.599
is a float that's greater or equal to zero. And finally, both of these columns are not

00:09:37.599 --> 00:09:42.919
nullable. Nullable equals false is actually a default, but I'm showing it here just to

00:09:42.919 --> 00:09:47.000
be explicit.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:54.179
So now that we've defined our schema, we can just call schema.validate. And if the data

00:09:54.179 --> 00:10:00.619
you pass into validate is valid, then it simply returns a valid data. So it applies

00:10:00.619 --> 00:10:06.619
a bunch of those checks. And if it's OK, you get your data, and you can continue whatever

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:09.299
you're doing with that data.

00:10:09.299 --> 00:10:18.500
However, if the data is invalid, so in this case, we're defining invalid data with a NAND

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:25.140
value in the price column and then squash as an item, which has a negative price, which

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:33.419
doesn't make sense unless I'm paying you $1,000 for squash. If I try validating this invalid

00:10:33.419 --> 00:10:39.659
data, I get a schema error. And if we catch that schema error, we can get the failure

00:10:39.659 --> 00:10:42.539
cases that Pandera found.

00:10:42.539 --> 00:10:47.539
In this case, Pandera is just going to kind of serially go through all those checks and

00:10:47.539 --> 00:10:54.619
raise the first one failure case it sees.

00:10:54.619 --> 00:10:58.739
Now that might not be good enough. I want to see what all the errors are. So there's

00:10:58.739 --> 00:11:05.580
a lazy equals true option keyword argument you can pass to the validate method. And if

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:12.539
you do that, Pandera will raise a schema errors exception. And in this case, the failure cases

00:11:12.539 --> 00:11:19.900
are a lot more informative. So we can see that failure cases is itself a data frame

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:25.820
that contains information about where the error happened, what column was the offending

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:33.059
column, which check was associated with failure, and the exact failure case value that caused

00:11:33.059 --> 00:11:39.859
this error, and then some bonus metadata of where the index was in the data frame.

00:11:39.859 --> 00:11:46.700
So as you can see, this package is really optimized for just sort of like data science,

00:11:46.700 --> 00:11:52.820
data engineers, ML engineers who are in the weeds in the code and kind of want to roll

