You can easily integrate this with your existing pipeline. So assuming that you have sort of

00:12:07.340 --> 00:12:13.020
functions defined for each step of your pipeline, this also works with methods, of course. But

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:16.539
in this case, we have a clean data function that doesn't do anything. It just returns

00:12:16.539 --> 00:12:25.419
the input. So this is the incorrect implementation. But in order to check the output of this function

00:12:25.419 --> 00:12:32.820
to make sure it conforms with the schema as we've defined it, we decorate the function

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:38.619
with this check types decorator. Of course, pass lazy equals true. And then we use type

00:12:38.619 --> 00:12:45.219
annotations to say, hey, this is a data frame that conforms with this schema. And once you've

00:12:45.219 --> 00:12:51.299
done this, clean data is now a data validator plus a function. So every time we call clean

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:58.539
data, we check all the values of the output. In this case, we recover the failure cases

