00:14:37.539 --> 00:14:42.659
to do it, by default, it's false.

00:14:42.659 --> 00:14:48.020
If you say ordered is true, then the raw data coming in needs to be in the same exact

00:14:48.020 --> 00:14:53.140
order as you specified in the schema. This is important to some people.

00:14:53.140 --> 00:14:58.780
Strict allows you to say, hey, I want to raise an error if there are random dangling columns

00:14:58.780 --> 00:15:04.580
that are just there in my data that aren't specified in my schema. I can actually say

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:09.179
strict equals filter, and it'll remove those columns.

00:15:09.179 --> 00:15:14.700
I can say drop invalid rows equals true, and any checks that fail are considered invalid

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:20.299
rows, and those are dropped if that's what you want. And then finally, unique column

00:15:20.299 --> 00:15:25.460
names is true, just does what it says. There are a few more options, but these just want

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:27.460
to give you a sampling.

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:34.419
There are also some built-in checks. So as you saw from that field function that's attached

